Tue Jul 9, 2026
14:12

I'm going to continue reading SICP, and I plan to spend the next couple of days
trying to build some small things in Scheme.

Interestingly, Scheme supports defining functions inside other functions (which
is impossible in C) - you just nest define. Also, Scheme has closures, just
like Python.

Section 1.2.1 covers linear recursion and linear iteration. Since I've studied
some algorithms before, I grasped this part quickly.

What's really cool, though, is the way SICP describes the expansion of linear
recursion.

Take this factorial program for example:
    (define (factorial n)
      (if (= n 1)
      1
      (* n (factorial (- n 1)))))

It's computation proceeds like an expansion followed by contraction - it
recurses all the way down to the base case, then unwinds back up, and then
interpreter has to remember every pending multiplication operation. As we all
know, its time complexity is O(n) and space complexity is also O(n). With an
iterative version, you don't see that expansion-contraction pattern; it can
archieve O(1) space complexity and has no risk of stack overflow.

