Tue Jul 7, 2026
15:42

Fixed a few issues that I hadn't noticed before:

* In Exercises 1.7 and 1.8, we need to add a precondition check to see if x is 0
  to avoid infinite loops. This is because 0.0 / 0.0 results in NaN (Not a
  Number) in mathematics.

  An interesting fact is that since NaN represents an undefinable number, it is
  not even equal to itself in most programming languages.

  Therefore, we can use the following expression to avoid NaN scenarios:

    (if (= x x) ...)

  Meanwhile, we can throw exceptions in Scheme using 'error', 'raise', or
  'guard'. All of these can be used smoothly in Chez Scheme.

* Due to translation issues, Exercise 1.3 is different in the English and
  Chinese versions. I have appended the English version of the exercise into the
  original ./sicp/p/1_3.scm file.

